    "created_at": "2023-05-10T01:27:22Z",
    "updated_at": "2023-05-10T01:40:01Z",
    "body": "Some distros (including Ubuntu in WSL) have the `$PLATFORM` var set to just `linux`, but if it's unset the `detect_platform` function in the install script sets it as `unknown-linux-musl` when `uname -s` returns `Linux`.\r\n\r\nAnd then it correctly states that `x86_64-linux` is not present in the supported targets (while `x86_64-unknown-linux-musl` is):\r\n\r\n```shell\r\nSUPPORTED_TARGETS=\"x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu x86_64-unknown-linux-musl \\\r\n                  i686-unknown-linux-musl aarch64-unknown-linux-musl \\\r\n                  arm-unknown-linux-musleabihf x86_64-apple-darwin \\\r\n                  aarch64-apple-darwin x86_64-pc-windows-msvc \\\r\n                  i686-pc-windows-msvc aarch64-pc-windows-msvc \\\r\n                  x86_64-unknown-freebsd\"\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo either the supported targets needs to have `x86_64-linux` added, or it should double check if the `$PLATFORM` var makes sense.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nMy current workaround is to download `install.sh` and add:\r\n\r\n```shell\r\nif [ \"$TARGET\" = \"x86_64-linux\" ]; then\r\n  TARGET=\"x86_64-unknown-linux-musl\"\r\nfi\r\n```\r\nafter `TARGET=\"$(detect_target \"${ARCH}\" \"${PLATFORM}\")\"` on line 482",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "pin": null,
